# Environment for AI coding agents

You are running inside [code-server](https://github.com/coder/code-server)
on a self-hosted [gpu-summon](https://github.com/dg1001/gpu-summon) box
(GPU rented from vast.ai). This file describes the environment so you can
make smart decisions about where to run things.

## Who you are

- Linux user: `coder` (passwordless `sudo` available — use sparingly)
- Default shell: bash
- Project root: `/workspace/projects` (you are likely already there)
- HF model cache: `/workspace/hf_cache` (read-only for normal use)

## Local LLM

A `llama-server` is running on this same box, GPU-backed. From here you
talk to it directly over loopback — no TLS, no internet hop:

- Endpoint: `http://localhost:8080/v1` (OpenAI-compatible)
- Bearer token: stored in opencode's auth file (see below)
- Model loaded: `${LLAMA_MODEL}`

`opencode` is pre-installed and pre-configured. From any terminal:

```bash
opencode
```

It already knows how to reach the local LLM. No further setup needed.

If you need to call the LLM from a script:

```bash
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $(jq -r '.[\"local-llamacpp\"].key' \
        ~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json)" \
     http://localhost:8080/v1/chat/completions \
     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
     -d '{"model": "MODEL_ID_FROM_/v1/models", "messages": [...]}'
```

## Web apps you start in a terminal

If you start a dev server (Flask, Vite, FastAPI, etc.), bind it to
`0.0.0.0:<port>` (or `127.0.0.1:<port>`) and it becomes publicly
reachable at:

```
https://<port>.${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/
```

Examples (replace `<port>` with whatever you bound to):

- Flask `app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)` → `https://5000.${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/`
- Vite (default 5173) → `https://5173.${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/`
- FastAPI uvicorn `:8000` → `https://8000.${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/`

**Pattern uses a DOT, not a hyphen** — duckdns wildcards work for
`*.${DOMAIN}` (third-level subdomains), not for sibling names with a
hyphen.

This **subdomain-per-port** pattern (rather than path-based proxying like
code-server's built-in `/proxy/<port>/`) means relative URLs in your app's
HTML/JS stay correct — links to `/api/foo`, `<form action="/submit">`, etc.
all resolve naturally.

**Avoid** `https://${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/proxy/<port>/` (the URL
code-server's "Open in Browser" button suggests for a forwarded port) —
every relative URL inside the rendered page will break (it goes to
code-server's root, not your app). Type the dot-subdomain URL above
into the address bar instead.

**Annoyance with the VS Code Ports tab:** The "Forwarded Address" column
shows the dot-subdomain pattern correctly but **without the host port
suffix** (e.g. `https://5000.${DOMAIN}/` instead of
`https://5000.${DOMAIN}<HOST_PORT_SUFFIX>/`). This is a VS Code parser
limitation — its URL builder strips non-standard ports from
`VSCODE_PROXY_URI`. There's no fix from code-server's side. Workaround:
copy the URL and append the host port manually in your browser address
bar. Goes away if/when this box is migrated to a provider that gives a
real public IP with port 443 (TensorDock, RunPod KVM, etc.).

## Ports already in use on this box

| Port | Used by | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| 8080 | llama-server | don't use this for your apps |
| 8443 | code-server | this is the IDE you're inside |
| 80 / 443 | Caddy | reverse proxy, TLS, routing |

Anything else (3000, 5000, 5173, 8000, 8888, ...) is yours.

## Persistence

This entire box is **ephemeral** — when the user runs `summon.py --destroy`,
everything is gone. To keep work:

- `git push` to a remote (GitHub etc.) before the user destroys
- The launcher does NOT do automatic backups

## When you're stuck

- LLM not responding? `tail /var/log/llama-server.log` (sudo)
- Port-forward not reaching your app? `tail /var/log/caddy.log` (sudo)
- IDE is slow? `nvidia-smi` to confirm the LLM isn't pegging GPU 100%

You generally have a fast GPU here, so feel free to run inference-heavy
agentic loops via `opencode` without worrying about latency.
